We are going to add the continent information, using the country code from variable flag_gfw We can do this with the countrycode library.

#install.packages("countrycode") # in case you don't have it ;)

We will now, tidy up the table, and will remove all observations with NA

tidy_data_vessels <- wide_data_vessels %>% 
  pivot_longer(names_to = "year",values_to = "fishing_hours", paste0("fishing_hours_",2012:2020)) %>%
  mutate(year = gsub("fishing_hours_","",year)) %>%
  drop_na()

Counts of total vessels per country

We want to explore the data on how many vessels are included in the dataset for each country. We will use the continent as a factor to compare differences among countries.

We could use count() on the tidy data table

vessel_count_tidy <- tidy_data_vessels %>% group_by(continent, flag_gfw) %>% count()

However, if we use the long (tidy) dataset, there can be several lines for each ship. Then, we have to use the wide dataset, since it has a row for every vessel.

vessel_count <- wide_data_vessels %>% group_by(continent, flag_gfw) %>% count()
vessel_count

To be sure that the identifiers of the vessels are unique, using distinct() on the wide dataset

unique_ships <- wide_data_vessels %>% select(mmsi) %>% distinct()

The number of rows is the same than the original. So all vessel mmsi values are unique.

A more detailed way of checking it.

wide_data_vessels %>%
  group_by(mmsi) %>%
  summarise(n = n()) %>%
  summary(n)

Plots with a single numeric variable and a categorical factor

Here, we are going to produce our first ggplot:

geom_point() (one numeric variable vs a categorical factor)

vessel_count %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n)) +
  geom_point()

There is one country that has many more vessels than the others (possibly China). We can filter it out

vessel_count_no_china <- vessel_count %>% filter(n != max(vessel_count$n))

vessel_count_no_china %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n)) +
  geom_point()

This looks better!

We can improve the visualization using geom_jitter() and alpha colours:

vessel_count_no_china %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.25, alpha = 0.4)

And we can add some colour.

vessel_count_no_china %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n, color=continent)) +
  geom_jitter(width = 0.25, alpha = 0.4, size = 3)

We can select boxplot geometry:

vessel_count_no_china %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n, color=continent)) +
  geom_boxplot()

Compare to this:

vessel_count_no_china %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=continent))

Or we can use violin plots:

vessel_count_no_china  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n)) +
  geom_violin(aes(fill=continent))

Perhaps it is a good idea to transform the y axis to log (log10)

vessel_count_no_china  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n)) +
  geom_violin(aes(fill=continent)) + 
  scale_y_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x)))

Learn more about using scales() here: https://r4ds.had.co.nz/graphics-for-communication.html?q=scale#scales

Now, we can bring China data back:

vessel_count  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n)) +
  geom_violin(aes(fill=continent)) + 
  scale_y_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) 

vessel_count  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=continent)) + 
  scale_y_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x)))

Adding two layers of geometries to the same plot

vessel_count  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=continent,y=n)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=continent)) + 
  geom_jitter(width = 0.25, alpha = 0.4, size = 2) + 
    scale_y_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x)))

Let’s reorder the x-axis by the median value:

vessel_count  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(continent,n,median),y=n)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(fill=continent)) + 
  geom_jitter(width = 0.25, alpha = 0.4, size = 2) + 
  scale_y_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x)))

Barplots

Barplots are useful to represent a summarizing variable for each group of the data.

We want to generate a barplot of the total number of vessels per country included in our data set for every continent.

We will produce a barplot of the total number of vessels per continent:

vessel_count %>% group_by(continent) %>% summarise(Total=sum(n)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(continent,Total),y=Total)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity",aes(fill=continent))

If we want horizontal bars, labels and log scale in the axis:

vessel_count %>% group_by(continent) %>% summarise(Total=sum(n)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(continent,Total),y=Total)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity",aes(fill=continent),color="black") +
  coord_flip() +
  geom_text(aes(label=Total), hjust=-0.1, size=2.5) +
  scale_y_log10(
  breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
  labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x)))

If we want to add the error bars, we have to calculate the sd in the summarise function

vessel_count %>% group_by(continent) %>% summarise(Total=sum(n), sd=sd(n)) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=reorder(continent,Total),y=Total)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity",aes(fill=continent),color="black") +
  coord_flip() +
  geom_text(aes(label=Total), hjust=-1.2, size=2.5) +
  scale_y_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) +
    geom_errorbar(aes(ymin=Total, ymax=Total+sd), width=.2)

Plots with one numerical variable and an ordered factor

Line plots

We will group by continent and will summarise the total sum of fishing hours. Let’s plot the total hours by year, to see the temporal trend by continent: *For that, we need to will return to the tidy dataset.

tidy_data_vessels %>% group_by(continent, year) %>% 
  summarise(Total_hours=sum(fishing_hours),sd=sd(fishing_hours),count=n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=year,y=Total_hours)) +
  geom_line(aes(color=continent,group=continent))+
  scale_y_log10(
  breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
  labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) 
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'continent'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Plots with two numerical variables

Scatter plot

We can calculate the total tonnage and the total fishing hours for each country and we will represent this in a scatterplot: As usual, we need to log-transform due to the values of China.

tidy_data_vessels %>% group_by(continent, flag_gfw) %>% 
  summarise(Total_hours=sum(fishing_hours),Total_tonnage=sum(tonnage_gt_gfw),count=n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Total_tonnage,y=Total_hours)) +
  geom_point() +
  scale_y_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) +
  scale_x_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) 
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'continent'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Facet_wrap

We will draw several panels depending on the values of a categorical variable. Here the categorical variable is continent.

tidy_data_vessels %>% group_by(continent, flag_gfw) %>% 
  summarise(Total_hours=sum(fishing_hours),Total_tonnage=sum(tonnage_gt_gfw),count=n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Total_tonnage,y=Total_hours)) +
  geom_point(aes(color=continent)) +
  scale_y_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) +
  scale_x_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1)) +
  facet_wrap(~ continent)
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'continent'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Add can a trend line (from a linear model):

tidy_data_vessels %>% group_by(continent, flag_gfw) %>% 
  summarise(Total_hours=sum(fishing_hours),Total_tonnage=sum(tonnage_gt_gfw),count=n()) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=Total_tonnage,y=Total_hours)) +
  geom_point(aes(color=continent)) +
  scale_y_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) +
  scale_x_log10(
    breaks = scales::trans_breaks("log10", function(x) 10^x),
    labels = scales::trans_format("log10", scales::math_format(10^.x))) +
  facet_wrap(~ continent) +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, vjust = 0.5, hjust=1)) +
  geom_smooth(formula = y ~ x, method="lm",color="black", linewidth=0.5) 
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'continent'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Distribution of a quantitative variable

Histograms and density plots

Now we want to explore how the fishing time per vessel is distributed for the different continents:

tidy_data_vessels  %>% 
ggplot(aes(x=log(fishing_hours))) +
  geom_histogram(aes(group=continent,fill=continent))+
  facet_wrap(~ continent) 
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 79 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_bin()`).

We can read more about grouping in aesthetics here: https://ggplot2.tidyverse.org/reference/aes_group_order.html

The counts are very different for each continent. We would like to have independent scale in Y:

tidy_data_vessels  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=log(fishing_hours))) +
  geom_histogram(aes(group=continent,fill=continent))+
  facet_wrap(~ continent,scales = "free_y") 
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.
## Warning: Removed 79 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_bin()`).

We can smooth the curves using geom_density()

tidy_data_vessels  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=log(fishing_hours))) +
  geom_density(aes(group=continent, fill=continent), alpha=.5)+
  facet_wrap(~ continent,scales = "free_y") 
## Warning: Removed 79 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_density()`).

And now we can explore the change over the years:

tidy_data_vessels  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=log(fishing_hours))) +
  geom_density(aes(group=continent, fill=continent),alpha=0.5)+
  facet_wrap(~ year,scales = "free_y") 
## Warning: Removed 79 rows containing non-finite values (`stat_density()`).

There are some apparent changes, but they are difficult to appreciate with these plots Let us change to geom_boxplot()

tidy_data_vessels  %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x=year)) +
  geom_boxplot(aes(y=log(fishing_hours),group=year, fill=continent), width=0.2)+
  geom_violin(aes(y=log(fishing_hours),group=year, fill=continent), alpha=.5)+
    facet_wrap(~ continent,scales = "free_y")
